    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="154"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14685: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-25T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 25, 1943—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>137. Reference Department’s telegram to Chungking, no. 58, March 13, 1941<note
                        n="6" xml:id="d154fn6">
                        <ref target="frus1941v05#pg_490">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 490</ref>.</note> and Embassy’s telegram
                    no. 114, March 26, 1941.<note n="7" xml:id="d154fn7">
                        <ref target="frus1941v05#pg_492">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 492</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>A report has reached us, presumably based on statements made by Edgar Snow<note
                        n="8" xml:id="d154fn8">Correspondent in China for the <hi rend="italic"
                            >Saturday Evening Post</hi> and author of <hi rend="italic">Red Star
                            Over China</hi> (1938).</note> and Chou En-lai, to the effect that, due
                    to such factors I as (1) deteriorating economic condition of the people in areas
                    under the control of the National Government, (2) deterioration of the National
                    Government’s armies resulting from economic and financial situation and from the
                    static condition of China’s warfare against Japan, and (3) the growing strength
                    of the Chinese communist armies through defections from National Government
                    armies and sale of arms to communist forces by soldiers of the National
                    Government armies, the National Government may in the near future take
                    repressive steps against the communists which might result in outbreak of civil
                    war.</p>
                <p>The Department would appreciate your views, without your making specific
                    inquiries outside the Embassy, in regard to the foregoing report.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
